Fit a regression tree to the training set

library(rpart)
##

##     prune
Carseats_model <- rpart(Sales ~ ., data = Carseats_train, method = 'anova')

1.Plot the tree and interpret the results

library(rpart.plot)
pa_pal_2tone <- colorRampPalette(c("#DFBAD3", "#E6B8D4", "#BAD8F6", "#9FBBFC"))

Carseats_model %>% 
  rpart.plot(
    roundint = FALSE,
    box.palette = pa_pal_2tone(6),
    type = 1,
    extra = 101,
    tweak = 1.1
  )

2.What test MSE do you obtain? 2.What test MSE do you obtain?

# Make predictions on the test set
predictions <- predict(Carseats_model, new_data = Carseats_test)

# Calculate Mean Squared Error
test_mse <- mean((predictions - Carseats_test$Sales)^2)
## Warning in predictions - Carseats_test$Sales: longer object length is not a
## multiple of shorter object length
print(paste("Test MSE:", round(test_mse, 3)))
## [1] "Test MSE: 13.409"

answer

  • The MSE I obtained is 13.409

# Evaluate the pruned tree on the test set

pruned_mse <- mean((pruned_predictions - Carseats_test$Sales)^2)
print(paste("Pruned Test MSE:", round(pruned_mse, 3)))
## [1] "Pruned Test MSE: 3.784"

answer

  • From the results, pruning does not necessarily increase or decrease MSE, which is determined by the performance of the model itself obtained from the training set data.

Q2

In this exercise, we will predict the number of applications received (Apps) using the other variables in the College data set. It contains several variables for 777 different universities and colleges in the US. The variables are

Private: Public/private indicator

Apps: Number of applications received

Accept: Number of applicants accepted

Enroll: Number of new students enrolled

Top10perc: New students from top 10 % of high school class

Top25perc: New students from top 25 % of high school class

F.Undergrad: Number of full-time undergraduates

P.Undergrad: Number of part-time undergraduates

Outstate: Out-of-state tuition

Room.Board: Room and board costs

Books: Estimated book costs

Personal: Estimated personal spending

PhD: Percent of faculty with Ph.D.s

Terminal: Percent of faculty with terminal degree

S.F.Ratio: Student/faculty ratio

perc.alumni: Percent of alumni who donate

Expend: Instructional expenditure per student

Grad.Rate: Graduation rate

a

Split the data set into a training set and a test set

Hint: choose some numbers or proportion that you find appropriate))

College<- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kwan-MSDA/MSDA7003/refs/heads/main/College.csv")
## Rows: 777 Columns: 18
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (1): Private
## dbl (17): Apps, Accept, Enroll, Top10perc, Top25perc, F.Undergrad, P.Undergr...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
set.seed(1234)
#
College<- College %>%
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)
#
data_split <- initial_split(College, prop = 0.7)
College_train <- training(data_split)
College_test <- testing(data_split)

b

Fit a linear model using least squares on the training set

Report the test error obtained

# Fit a linear regression model
lm.fit<- lm(Apps~., data = College_train)
# Compute the test MSE
lm.pred<- predict(lm.fit, College_test)
lm_test_MSE<- mean((lm.pred - College_test$Apps)^2)
print(paste("Test MSE:", round(lm_test_MSE, 2)))
## [1] "Test MSE: 826006.83"

c

Fit a ridge regression model on the training set, with chosen by cross-validation.

Report the test error obtained.

#install.packages("glmnet")
library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'Matrix'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     expand, pack, unpack
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-8
library(tidyverse)
library(glmnet)

# Fit a ridge regression model
x<- model.matrix(Apps~., data = College_train)[,-1]
y<- College_train$Apps
ridge.fit<- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0)
plot(ridge.fit, xvar = "lambda")

cv.fit_ridge<- cv.glmnet(x, y, type.measure = "mse", nfolds = 10, alpha = 0)
ridge_cv.pred_min<- predict(cv.fit_ridge, s = cv.fit_ridge$lambda.min, newx = model.matrix(Apps~., data =College_test)[,-1])
cat("the mean square test error for min lambda" , mean((ridge_cv.pred_min - College_test$Apps)^2), "\n")
## the mean square test error for min lambda 849404.4

Fit a lasso model on the training set, with chosen by cross-validation

Report the test error obtained

What is the number of non-zero coefficient estimates?
